		</table></td><td class="PanelBody" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">What if the new level cap was 75?<a name="39655"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 12 04 4:14 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I have a theory that the new level cap may in fact be going to 75, not 70. It's really out on a limb, but I have found some mathematical circumstantial evidence that points to that as a possibility.
<br />

<br />
It is derived from the rumor that the new levels will be based on AA's, or uses AA's to unlock them. The 1-level-per-every-100-AA's idea isn't bad, but I think if it is done that way then you will still see many level 65 players and many with their level maxed at 70 or 75 with fewer in between. One of the problems with the game today is that so many characters are level 65 that level has little  real meaning anymore. I think it is more likely that this type of a system would use a graduated scale, like taxes are or something.
<br />

<br />
Pulling out a calculator and doing some simple math, I wondered what if every title such as baron, veteran, or impresario was bestowed a new level. All the barons wiould be level 66, all the veterans 67, and all the impresarios 68... what would the levels beyond 68 look like, and what number of AA's might you need to get to them?
<br />

<br />
The formula I came up with was <i>l</i>+<i>x</i>=<i>n</i>, where <i>l</i> is current AA's and <i>x</i> is an incremental modifier of 12 added on every level to determine the new number of AA's needed to advance.
<br />

<br />
If you need 6 AA's to get lvl66, 18 to get lvl67, and 42 to get 68, the most reasonable mathematical progression to me was 78, since:
<br />
6+12=18 (to get veteran or level 67),
<br />
18+24=42, (to get impresario or level 68), and
<br />
42+36=78 (to get to level 69).
<br />

<br />
I decided that adding 12 cumulatively every time to the current tally was the most natural curve that could be constructed out of the existing pattern of progression. Continuing this trend gave the following results:
<br />
78+48=126 (to get to level 70),
<br />
126+60=186 (to get to level 71),
<br />
186+72=258 (to get to level 72),
<br />
258+84=342 (to get to level 73),
<br />
342+108=438 (to get to level 74),
<br />
438+120=546 (to get to level 75).
<br />

<br />
The reason I stopped at 75 and not 70 or 80 was because (if I remember correctly) the current AA max is 650. Someone please tell me if this number is wrong.
<br />

<br />
The sheer number of players today all capped at the same level of 65 is far beyond what it ever has before. The only people I know who aren't 65 have been playing a year or less. For this reason alone, to bring some disparity back into the game, I think that they may be going straight to 75. It seems to me to be the most reasonable solution to the problem.
<br />

<br />
Any thoughts?</span></td>
